          "title": "The geographic appendix: a province reoccupied",
          "body": "Verses 25-36 shift from the city to the countryside, cataloging the towns of Judah and Benjamin that have been resettled. The sweep is deliberate: Beersheba (the ancient southern boundary) to the Valley of Hinnom (Jerusalem's own edge) for Judah (11:30); Geba, Michmash, Bethel, Anathoth, Ramah, and Lod for Benjamin (11:31-35). These are not random villages. Kiriath-arba is Hebron, the city of Abraham and David (Josh. 14:15; 2 Sam. 2:1-4). Beersheba is where Abraham dug a well and where Elijah fled in exhaustion (Gen. 21:31; 1 Kgs. 19:3). Anathoth is Jeremiah's hometown (Jer. 1:1), the city from which the prophet prophesied the very return now being enacted. Lachish was the last city standing before Jerusalem fell to Babylon (Jer. 34:7). The chapter is reoccupying the entire drama of Israel's history, town by town. The final verse (11:36) — noting that some Levitical divisions 'in Judah belonged to Benjamin' — records a blending of tribal boundaries that reflects the post-exilic reality: the sharp tribal geography of Joshua has softened, but the covenant people remains."
